solution.p:
Critical points are those values of x in the domain of f(x) for which f'(x)=0, and singular points are those values of x in the domain of f(x) for which f(x) is not differentiable. So, we ought to find f'(x). Using the quotient rule,
f'(x)&=\frac{(x-5)(2x)-(x^2-10)}{(x-5)^2}
&=\frac{x^2-10x+10}{(x-5)^2}
The only place where this function doesn't exist is x=5. Since 5 is not in the domain of f(x),
(b) f(x) has no singular points.
To find the critical points, we find where f'(x)=0. That is: 0&=x^2-10x+10
Using the quadratic formula, x&=\dfrac{10\pm\sqrt{10^2-4(1)(10)}}{2}
&=5 \pm \sqrt{15}
(a) So the critical points of f(x) are x=5+\sqrt{15} and x=5-\sqrt{15}.

